# Project Planning & Task Breakdown

## Milestones

- [ ] **M1**: ZK circuit for note transactions (validity, nullifier, value conservation) compiles + passes tests
- [ ] **M2**: Agent WASM prover generates proofs locally in <100ms
- [ ] **M3**: Aggregator folds N proofs via Nova into one aggregate proof
- [ ] **M4**: Soroban verifier contract accepts and verifies aggregate proof
- [ ] **M5**: Bridge contract (deposit/withdraw) functional
- [ ] **M6**: End-to-end POC — two agents send private payments, aggregate proof settles to Stellar testnet

## Task Breakdown

### Phase 1: ZK Circuit Design

- [ ] **1.1** Design note circuit
  - Inputs: old_note_commitment, old_note_nullifier, new_note_commitment, value, fee, signature
  - Constraints: Poseidon hash, merkle proof, value conservation
  - Outcome: Circom or Halo2 circuit that compiles

- [ ] **1.2** Implement note circuit in Halo2
  - Reuse existing Poseidon2 implementation from `contracts/soroban-utils/`
  - Implement merkle tree verification in circuit
  - Outcome: Halo2 circuit, passes test with known inputs

- [ ] **1.3** Add Nova proof step circuit
  - Wrap note circuit in Nova step (R1CS → IVC)
  - Outcome: `NoteProofStep` circuit — proves one note transaction

### Phase 2: Agent Prover (WASM)

- [ ] **2.1** Port prover to Halo2 (replace Groth16)
  - Current prover: `app/crates/core/prover/` uses Groth16
  - New prover: Halo2/Nova proving path
  - Outcome: `cargo build --target wasm32-unknown-unknown` produces WASM

- [ ] **2.2** Benchmark prover in WASM
  - Measure proof generation time for one note transaction
  - Target: <100ms
  - Outcome: Benchmarks, identified bottlenecks

- [ ] **2.3** WASM runtime integration
  - Verify prover works in browser (WebAssembly) and Node.js
  - Outcome: WASM module loads and generates proofs in both envs

### Phase 3: Aggregator

- [ ] **3.1** Implement Nova folding
  - Take `NoteProofStep` proofs from agents
  - Fold into one aggregate proof via Nova recursion
  - Outcome: Aggregate proof verifiable on Stellar

- [ ] **3.2** Aggregator service
  - HTTP endpoint for agents to submit proofs
  - Batching logic: fold N proofs before submitting to chain
  - Outcome: Service that aggregates and submits

- [ ] **3.3** Aggregator激励机制 (POC: permissioned)
  - POC uses single centralized aggregator
  - No token bribe or decentralized consensus yet

### Phase 4: Soroban Verifier Contract

- [ ] **4.1** Soroban ZK verifier
  - Investigate: does Soroban have built-in ZK verification for Halo2/Nova?
  - If no: implement G1/G2 point arithmetic + pairing check in Soroban
  - Outcome: `verify_aggregate_proof` function on Soroban

- [ ] **4.2** Rollup state contract
  - Store `state_root`, `nullifier_root`, `block_height`
  - `verify_aggregate_proof` updates state
  - Outcome: Contract stores and updates rollup state

- [ ] **4.3** Bridge contract (modify existing pool)
  - Existing `contracts/pool/` handles token custody
  - Add deposit/withdraw for bridging
  - Outcome: Users can bridge tokens to rollup

### Phase 5: End-to-End POC

- [ ] **5.1** Agent A → Agent B private payment
  - Both agents generate ZK proofs locally
  - Proofs submitted to aggregator
  - Aggregate proof settles to Stellar
  - Outcome: Private payment visible on-chain only as aggregated state diff

- [ ] **5.2** Deposit + withdraw flow
  - User deposits tokens to bridge
  - User sends private payment via rollup
  - Recipient withdraws from bridge
  - Outcome: Full round-trip works

## Dependencies

```
1.1 (circuit design) → 1.2 (implement Halo2) → 1.3 (Nova step)
                                                    │
1.2 ───────────────────────────────────────────────┘
        │
        ▼
2.1 (port prover to Halo2) ──► 2.2 (benchmark) ──► 2.3 (WASM runtime)
        │
        │◄──────────────────────────────────────────┘
        │
        ▼
3.1 (Nova folding) ──► 3.2 (aggregator service) ──► 3.3 (POC aggregator)
        │
        ▼
4.1 (Soroban ZK verifier) ──► 4.2 (rollup state) ──► 4.3 (bridge contract)
        │
        └────────────────────────────┬───────────────┘
                                    ▼
                            5.1 (E2E agent→agent)
                                    │
                                    ▼
                            5.2 (deposit+withdraw)
```

**Key sequencing notes**:
- Phase 1 and 2 are sequential — circuit drives prover
- Phase 3 can start after Phase 2.1 (proof generation works)
- Phase 4 (Soroban) can start in parallel with Phase 3 — aggregator and verifier are independent until integration
- Phase 5 requires Phase 3 + 4 complete

